\par Who will win as this slow-motion confrontation between humankind and nature goes on? No one really knows. But after watching Mt. St. Helens and listening to the guesses about its performance, if we had to bet, we would bet on the river.
\par The Corps had alrea
dy seen that bet, and was about to bump it, too. Even before the muds were dry from the 1973 flood, Corps engineers had begun building a model of Old River at their Waterways Experiment Station, in Vicksburg. The model was to cover an acre and a half. A m
o
del of that size was modest for the Corps. Not far away, it had a fifteen-acre model of the Mississippi drainage, where water flowing in from the dendritic tips could get itself together and attack Louisiana. The scale was one human stride to the mile. In
 the time it took to say \'93one Mississippi,\'94 if fourteen gallons went past Arkansas City that was a Project Flood. Something like eight and a half gallon was \'93a high-water event.\'94 \'93It\rquote s the ultimate sandbox\emdash 
