\par Soileau said, \'93I hear you get only three or four.\'94
\par Bourque had a recipe of which the nouveaux cuisiniers may not have heard. \'93Saut\'e9 onions in butter, then put in fat out of the head for ten or fifteen minutes, then put meat in for a few minutes more,\'94 he said. \'93
Salt. Cayenne pepper. Onion tops. What makes the \'e9touff\'e9e is the fat. Some people put a little roux in there. You can stretch it like that.\'94 Crawfish \'e9touff\'e9
e: the Cajun quenelle de brochet. The meat is ground, but not to the end of texture. On Easter Sunday morning in Catahoula, the Bourques have a crawfish ball. At least, I thought that\rquote 
s what they were saying until I saw what they did. They boiled a hundred pounds of crawfish. They ate a crimson mountain of condensed lobsters.
