A willow branch eaten by a beaver is just as smooth as if it had been sanded,\'94 Soileau remarked. \'93There\rquote s nothing prettier than a willow branch eaten by a beaver.\'94
 Nutria live in the swamp as well. Bourque said that he sees only four or five alligators a year. A friend of his lost a finger to a cottonmouth. \'93
He was walking through thick lilies, very high lilies, to make a road for his pirogue. The snake bit his finger through a glove.\'94 Among the crowns of the cypress, a heron flapped by. Bourque called it a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
